          SECTION 2.0 NETWORK OVERVIEW          ____________________________




          SECTION 2.1 General Description          _______________________________


          A  TYMNET network  consists of  a  collection of  minicomputers
          (nodes) interconnected by communication lines to allow informa-
          tion to  travel along  alternative paths  between nodes  in the
          network.  The primary  function of a  node is to  pass informa-
          tion.   The nodes,  typically, do  little or  no processing  of
          application tasks.  Nodes  have buffers which are  used to hold
          data en route to another node or to a terminal or host port.

          TYMNET  technology provides  the flexibility  of designing  and
          building a network  in a nearly  infinite number  of configura-
          tions.  Customers may  choose to configure the  network to suit
          their  particular needs.   A TYMNET  network  consists of  four
          major types of components, examples of  which are shown in Fig-
          ure 1 and which are described below.

          In general, all  nodes are switchers and  contain basic routing
          and flow control.   They may  also contain  one of  these func-
          tions:  terminal interface, host interface,  gateway, or Super-
          visor.  However, in the case of  an ISIS node, several of these
          functions may run concurrently in one  network node.  (See Sec-
          tion 3.2.6 for more detail on ISIS.)

          Additionally, a fifth  network support function is  provided in
          the form of  the optional Network Control  Center (NCC).  Refer
          to Section 4.0 for more details on NCC components.

          The TYMNET  Engine is  used as  the processor  for the  network
          node.  Its configuration can be tailored  to match the applica-
          tion.


















