          2.1.1 Network Supervisor                __________________


          The network  Supervisor is the heart  of a TYMNET  network.  It
          performs the following functions within the network.

          A)   It controls user login.  This  includes verifying that the
               user is a valid network user,  limiting the user access to
               certain nodes or hosts, issuing  network messages at login
               time about the availability of nodes  or hosts, and build-
               ing a  circuit for each  session through the  network from
               the point of origination to the point of termination.

          B)   The Supervisor  collects accounting  information for  each
               circuit which is built in the network and stores it onto a
               disk file on the Supervisor machine.

          C)   The Supervisor  receives error  messages from  the various
               network nodes  and interfaces and stores  this information
               on a disk file.

          D)   The Supervisor monitors the state of all nodes in the net-
               work, and maintains a current image  of the network topol-
               ogy and resource utilization.

          E)   A process  called PROBE  exists on  each Supervisor  node.
               PROBE allows a network operator to  inquire about the con-
               dition of each node and host on the network, their associ-
               ated circuits,  if any, and  provides commands  to control
               access as required.   In addition, PROBE allows  a user to
               monitor the error log information in real time.


          2.1.2 Terminal Interface                __________________


          The TYMNET terminal interface is referred  to as a TYMSAT.  The
          Asynchronous TYMSAT provides  the interface to a  large variety
          of ASCII asynchronous  devices.  This module exists  both under
          ISIS and  as a stand-alone  node.  The Asynchronous  TYMSAT can
          also provide control  of a local line  printer device operating
          as a high speed  ASCII output terminal with  special host soft-
          ware  support.  The  Asynchronous TYMSAT  provides the  control
          which is specific to the  type of asynchronous device attached.
          It detects connect  and disconnect of the  device.  It performs
          serialization/deserialization of  the characters  going to  and
          coming from the device.  It also  echoes most of the characters
          it receives  from the  device.  In  some cases  of full  duplex
          operation,  the Asynchronous  TYMSAT  must  defer to  the  host
          interface to determine  how characters should be  echoed.  (See
          Section 3.2.3 for more detail on TYMSATs.)




