          2.1.3 Host Interface                ______________


          The TYMNET host interfaces  include Asynchronous TYMCOMs, X.25,
          X.75,  3270, and  2780/3780.   The  typical customer's  network
          includes two types of host interfaces - Asynchronous TYMCOM and
          X.25.

          The Asynchronous  TYMCOM appears to  the host  as a set  of low
          speed  asynchronous modems.   This module  runs  on the  TYMNET
          Engine under ISIS.   (See Section 3.2.4 for more  detail on the
          host interfaces.)

          The TYMNET  X.25 interface serves as  a network interface  to a
          host, and provides access to a  host on a TYMNET public network
          or a customer  host in a private network.   It allows terminals
          on the network  to build circuits to the host  computer, and it
          also allows the host computer to  build circuits to other hosts
          on the network.

          The  TYMNET X.75  interface  allows  two public  data  networks
          (PDNs) to transmit data.  The  process involves the transfer of
          information between two signalling terminals, each within a PDN
          and connected by an international link.

          The 3270  interface provides  the  interface  between the  cus-
          tomer's IBM 3270  terminal and  support host  through the  cus-
          tomer's   TYMNET   network.   The   3270   interface   provides
          3270-terminal   access   to  computers   with   3270   support,
          3270-terminal access to computers with ASCII support, and ASCII
          CRT access to computers with  3270 support.  The interface also
          provides  multi-host/multi-application support  for 3270  users
          connected to a TYMNET network.

          The 2780/3780 interface provides  data communication for remote
          batch terminals (RBTs)  to host computers with  2780, 3780, and
          3770 series RJE terminal support through a TYMNET network.

          ISIS  nodes have special  host-like characteristics.  A circuit
          can  be built  to  the Kernel  of the  ISIS  node.  The  Kernel
          inspects the user name in the login stream and routes data from
          that circuit  to a  subprocess which  runs on  the node.   This
          function is described  in more detail in Section  3.2.6 of this
          document.











