          SECTION 2.2 Performance Criteria          ________________________________




          2.2.1 Network Delay                _____________


          The network  delay for a  circuit is  the algebraic sum  of the
          delays for each  process through which the data  must pass.  At
          the end  points, the amount of  delay depends on  the interface
          process.  For  the links along the  path, it is  almost totally
          dependent on  the line speed,  except for  anomalous situations
          involving line errors requiring  retransmissions.  Following is
          a table containing the average delay times for links of various
          speeds.  These numbers assume the line  is not completely satu-
          rated.  They  include both transmission  time for a  packet and
          holding time within a node until a  new packet can be transmit-
          ted.


                         LINK SPEED        AVERAGE ONE WAY DELAY
                          (KB/SEC)                 (MS.)
                         ----------        ---------------------
                            2.4                    220
                            4.8                    110
                            9.6                     55
                           56                       9


          2.2.2 Access Time                ___________


          Network access time  is defined as the time from  when the user
          types the  character terminating the  password entry  until the
          host  receives an  indication that  a  circuit to  it has  been
          built.  Assuming that no anomalies such as node outages or link
          outages occur  during the circuit  building process,  this time
          for a typical  Network (one of 100  nodes or less with  a login
          rate less than or equal to 60 per minute) is less than two sec-
          onds 90%  of the time,  and less than  four seconds 99%  of the
          time.

          The login  response time will  include both the  network access
          time and the time required for the  host to respond to the user
          login.  The apparent delay to the user may be much greater than
          the network access time.








