          2.2.3 Network Availability                ____________________


          Network availability is  a function of network  node, line, and
          Supervisor availability.  Availability is  thus affected by the
          design of the network hardware,  the networking technology, the
          reliability of the communication lines, and the particular net-
          work configuration.  Tymshare is able  to control the first two
          of these areas.   We have designed many features  into both the
          network hardware and software  to assure a high  degree of net-
          work availability.  Also, by use  of the network simulator, the
          customer  can analyze  network  configurations  to provide  for
          optimum network resource availability.

          A)   The TYMNET Engine

               The TYMNET Engine has been designed by Tymshare for use in
               TYMNET as well as private networks.   To this end, we have
               used over ten years  of experience to design  and manufac-
               ture hardware  that is both unlikely  to fail and  easy to
               repair if it does fail.  For more information on the reli-
               ability and availability of the TYMNET Engine, see Section
               3.1.

          B)   Alternate Pathing

               A TYMNET network is designed to allocate an available path
               when a circuit is to be built in the network.  Normally, a
               TYMNET network  is configured so  every node has  at least
               two connections to  other nodes in the  network.  Thus, if
               one  link fails,  circuits can  be built  across the  link
               which is still available.

               In TYMNET  I, if a link  or intermediate node goes  out of
               service, all the  active circuits using that  link will be
               broken and  the user will be  forced to log in  again.  In
               TYMNET II, when such an  event occurs, the Supervisor will
               automatically build a new circuit  if a path is available.
               Other than a  hesitation due to the  circuit building, the
               user will be unaware of the occurence of the link outage.

               When a link fails, the network can take up to 8 seconds to
               determine that the failure has  occurred.  The delay expe-
               rienced by  the user  will include this  8 seconds  plus 2
               seconds for each  50 circuits which were  using the failed
               link.

          C)   Supervisor Backup

               As is explained in Section 3.2.2, a Supervisor outage in a
               TYMNET network is not a catastrophe since currently active
               circuits are  unaffected, and multiple Supervisors  may be



