               provided.  In the case of a Supervisor failure in a TYMNET
               network,  a backup  Supervisor  wakes  up within  a  short
               period of time and takes over the network.  The supervisor
               can complete takeover  of 1 to 20 nodes in  30 seconds, 21
               to 100 nodes  in one minute, and  101 to 200 nodes  in two
               minutes.


          2.2.4 CPU Loading Considerations                __________________________


          The following CPU load characteristics must  be taken into con-
          sideration when configuring  or expanding a network  node.  The
          necessary calculations have  been automated in the  PRICER pro-
          gram.  This  program may  be used  by TYMNET  to verify  that a
          given node configuration is supportable.

          A)   Constant System Overhead

               The ISIS operating environment and several of the hardware
               devices create a constant system overhead on the CPU.  The
               ISIS system  imposes an overhead of  up to 25% of  the CPU
               depending on the particular configuration.  The ISIS over-
               head will vary according  to the number of  job slots con-
               figured, the types of interfaces running in each job slot,
               and the aggregate data throughput.

          B)   Protocol Handlers

               Network Links -

               The CPU load  imposed by network link  handling depends on
               the number of channels per  link (set at system generation
               time) and  on the  amount of  user data  passing over  the
               link.  Up  to 3.0% of the  CPU is required to  support 160
               channels.  Up to 2.5% of the  CPU is required to pass 1000
               cps  of user  data through  a node  (in one  link and  out
               another).

               Asynchronous TYMSAT -

               CPU utilization by the Asynchronous TYMSAT code depends on
               the number of ports and  the average input/output rates of
               these ports.   For an average of  one cps in and  four cps
               out on 256 ports, 30% of the CPU is needed.  The relation-
               ships tend to be linear so that  256 ports running at dou-
               ble the above  I/O rates use about 60% of  the CPU.  Input
               and output create approximately the same  load on the net-
               work.  Thus, I/O  rates of 4 cps  in and 1 cps  out create
               loads equivalent to 1 cps in and 4 cps out.





                                          Performance Criteria    Page 11



          Network Specifications                            July 11, 1980



               Non-TYMNET Synchronous Protocols -

               For  X.25, the  CPU utilization  per line  depends on  the
               amount of  user traffic transmitted  over the  line.  This
               figure is about 1.5% per 100 cps of user data.

               Supervisor -

               CPU utilization by  the network Supervisor is  nearly com-
               pletely  dependent on  the login  rate and  the number  of
               nodes in the network.  CPU  utilization for the Supervisor
               increases with  the login rates and  with the size  of the
               network.  The impact of network size  is a function of how
               long the average  virtual circuit becomes.  For  a 20 node
               network and a login rate of one per second, the Supervisor
               requires 5%  of the  CPU.  For  a 20  node network  with a
               login rate of 3 per second, the supervisor requires 15% of
               the CPU.  For networks of up to  100 nodes, the CPU utili-
               zation will not increase significantly  if sufficient net-
               work links are added to minimize  the number of intermedi-
               ate nodes for most user circuits.

          C)   Constant Communication Device Overhead.

               In addition to the constant system  overhead and the over-
               head  of the  protocol handlers,  a  constant overhead  is
               incurred  to  service  the  hardware  interrupts  for  the
               asynchronous  and  synchronous   communications  interface
               hardware.  This overhead  depends on the number  of lines,
               and the transmission speeds of the lines.

               The following loads are  imposed for communications device
               overhead, not  including any  additional overhead  for the
               protocol handler which services the device:

