          SECTION 2.3 Network Monitoring and Control          __________________________________________


          The active network  Supervisor is aware of the  status of every
          node, communication link, computer, any equipment in operation,
          errors occurring on  the communication  lines, and  load condi-
          tions of each  node in the network.   Additionally, the network
          Supervisor maintains a  complete chronological log of  all sig-
          nificant events in the  network.  This log is in the  form of a
          disk file which is maintained on the Supervisor node and can be
          read by building a circuit to the Supervisor node.  Examples of
          conditions reported are:

               o  any host computer down
               o  any node failure - such as power failure
               o  communication lines inoperative (unable to
                  pass data correctly)
               o  communication lines out of channels (capacity)
               o  communication line error rates (number of
                  retransmissions)


          2.3.1 PROBE                _____


          The Supervisor also permits manual  intervention and inquiry as
          to the status of any point  in a TYMNET network.  This function
          is referred to  as PROBE.  Examples of  PROBE functions include
          the ability to:

               o  examine network topology
               o  monitor login rate
               o  examine host conditions
               o  determine how many users are connected to a host
               o  determine where host users have originated a call
                  and which nodes they pass through en route
               o  stop new use of poor quality communication lines and
                  route new circuits over alternate paths


          2.3.2 Accounting Information                ______________________


          For monitoring purposes, a TYMNET network has available a chro-
          nological listing of each login that  shows the node from which
          the user  called, type of terminal,  user ID, port on  the host
          machine, time  on and off,  characters transmitted in  and out,
          and seconds connected.  A sort of this information gives valua-
          ble statistics about effectiveness of  the user's data communi-
          cations.





