          2.3.3 Network Monitoring                __________________


          The network  constantly performs  checks on  its resources  and
          monitors performance.  If any anomolies occur, they are immedi-
          ately reported  to PROBE where  simple language  messages alert
          personnel to the  situation.  Network operations can  then per-
          form inspection and  analysis of the situation  remotely and/or
          dispatch maintenance personnel as  appropriate.  The conditions
          reported include:  line  errors on links, temperature  of proc-
          essor in each node, interface ports running open, cross-talk on
          long-lines, loss of or illegal interrupts, and many others.

          A complete summary of network  monitoring messages is contained
          in the PROBE User's Guide.                 __________________


          2.3.4 Network Simulation                __________________


          TYMNET  provides a  network  simulation  program called  SIMNET
          which can be used to simulate network activity for various net-
          work  configurations.  Expected  network  traffic patterns  are
          passed to the simulator in the form  of a session file contain-
          ing records similar to those in the accounting information men-
          tioned above.  A  network topology is specified  as input files
          to the simulator.  Using this tool, it is possible to plan net-
          work expansion intelligently and  with a high degree  of confi-
          dence.


























