          3.1.3 Memory Access Controller Board                ______________________________


          The Memory Access Controller board (MAC) provides protection of
          memory by controlling access to it.

          The MAC partitions  physical memory address space  into logical
          address space.  At  system generation, each process  running in
          the node is  assigned its  own logical  address space.   There-
          after, the  process has access to,  and awareness of,  only its
          own  logical address  space.  The  same is  true of  peripheral
          devices attached to  the node.  Since the MAC  has control over
          the mapping of logical addresses  to physical memory locations,
          the process (or  device) is prevented, in  case of malfunction,
          from obtaining access  to, or writing over,  any memory address
          space not allocated to it.

          Two independent processes  might have the same  logical address
          for different real memory  locations.  Similarly, two processes
          might have  different logical addresses  for the  same physical
          memory area, to permit shared memory access.

          The MAC's handling of address  space enables selectable control
          of execute  inhibit access,  read only  access, and  read/write
          access.   Thus, the  MAC is  capable  of two  types of  address
          instruction checking.  Each addressing  instruction is screened
          to determine that it falls within  the range of logical address
          space allocated to the process  (or device) making the request.
          In addition, each such instruction  is checked for access type.
          The type of  access must correspond to the  access permitted to
          the process within the allowed logical address space.


          3.1.4 Synchronous Interface Board                ___________________________


          The synchronous  interface board provides  control of up  to 16
          synchronous lines.   Half of these  lines can contain  the data
          set control signals: Data Term Ready, Data Set Ready, and Clear
          to Send.  The other half  cannot.  Receive Data, Transmit Data,
          Receive Clock, Transmit Clock and Request to Send are supported
          on all lines.

          The maximum  speed of  any of these  synchronous lines  is 9600
          bits per  second.  The  board is capable  of supporting  all 16
          lines at 9600 bits per second.

          The interface signals provided conform to the EIA RS232C inter-
          face standards,  and are compatible  with CCITT  V.24 interface
          standards.





