          Network Specifications                            July 11, 1980



          If internal clocking is necessary, 4800 and 9600 bps clocks are
          available on all lines.

          The synchronous board interfaces to a  connector panel via rib-
          bon cables.   Cables which connect  to the terminals  or modems
          being controlled are connected via this connector panel.

          The synchronous board interfaces to the  I/O bus.  A maximum of
          two boards can be  installed in an Engine for a  capacity of 32
          synchronous lines in an Engine.


          3.1.5 Asynchronous Interface Board                ____________________________


          The asynchronous interface board provides  control for up to 32
          asynchronous communications  lines which  can be  in duplex  or
          half-duplex operation.

          Clocking for  all lines must  be done internally.   The maximum
          speed for any line is 1200 baud.

          In accordance with RS-232C signal protocol, control of six sig-
          nals is  provided for each line.   The signals provided  in the
          standard cables are  Carrier Detect, Data Term  Ready, Data Set
          Ready, Req to Send, Recv Data, and Xmit Data.

          The asynchronous board connects to the connector panel via rib-
          bon cables.

          The asynchronous board interfaces to the I/O bus.  A maximum of
          8 boards can be installed into an  Engine for a capacity of 256
          asynchronous lines.


