          SECTION 3.2 Network Software          ____________________________


          As  was mentioned  earlier, TYMNET  software  consists of  five
          basic functions.  These are the  Node Code, the Supervisor, the
          TYMCOM, the  TYMSAT, and  the Gateway.   A network  node always
          contains the Node  Code function.  In stand-alone  systems, the
          node also  contains one  of the  other functions.   In an  ISIS
          node, the node will contain the Node Code functions plus one or
          more  of the  other functions.   These functions  and ISIS  are
          described below.


          3.2.1 Node Code                _________


          Each network  node contains  routines to  perform the  function
          known as  the Node Code.  The  node code handles  the internode
          protocol, the tearing  down and building of  packets, modifica-
          tion of the permuter tables upon the command of the Supervisor,
          and the flow control of data across network links.


          A)   Internode Protocol

               Tymshare has developed its own  internal node-to-node pro-
               tocol for  intra-net data  transfers.  The  protocol is  a
               full duplex, error checking, ACK-with-data design which is
               much like X.25  level 2 only  highly tuned and  more effi-
               cient.  The protocol is described  in detail in supporting
               documentation.

               Data travels in the form of packets between network nodes.
               Each packet  may contain data  for several of  the network
               circuits using the link.  Each  packet is checksummed with
               a 32 bit checksum.  When a  packet is received with a good



                                              Network Software    Page 23



          Network Specifications                            July 11, 1980



               checksum, a  corresponding acknowledgement  is sent  along
               with data  in the  next packet  transmitted back  over the
               link.  This TYMNET technology tends to reduce the overhead
               of data packets by multiplexing data traveling in the same
               direction into single packets.

               The TYMNET  I packet format  is indicated  below.  Several
               different TYMNET II  packet formats also exist.   A packet
               can consist of several logical records relating to differ-
               ent users.  The  maximum length of the packet  is 66 bytes
               and  the fixed  overhead  is 6  bytes.   Each user's  data
               within a packet has a two byte header.  The header is fol-
               lowed by the  data.  The packet can consist of  at most 20
               different users' data (one character per user).

               +-----------------------------//--------------------------+
               |         |       |       |       |       |       |       |
               |  2 byte | 2 byte|       |       | 2 byte|       | 4 byte|
               |  packet | header| data  | ----- | header| data  | check-|
               |  header |  for  |  for  |  ...  |  for  |  for  | sum   |
               |         | user 1| user 1|       | user N| user N|       |
               +----|----|---|---|---|---|---//--|---|---|---|---|-|-|-|-+

          B)   Buffer and Channel Allocation

               A circuit going into a network node is allocated one logi-
               cal channel  on the link  it uses  to "enter" the  node in
               TYMNET I.  Each link in a TYMNET  network has a fixed num-
               ber of channels  which are assigned when the  Node Code is
               generated.

               In TYMNET II,  the number  of links  is dynamically  allo-
               cated.  A channel is  assigned to a circuit  when the cir-
               cuit is built,  and the circuit retains  the exclusive use
               of that channel until the circuit is torn down.  If a cir-
               cuit passes through a node, it  is also assigned a channel
               on the  link it uses to  "exit" the node.  Enter  and exit
               are misnomers  in that the  circuit is full  duplex.  They
               are used here simply for descriptive purposes.

               Additionally, each circuit in a  network node is allocated
               a pair of buffers when the  circuit is built.  Each buffer
               handles the data  flowing in one  direction over  the cir-
               cuit.  These buffers are dynamic and require no space when
               empty.

               In TYMNET I, these channels and  buffers are assigned spe-
               cifically by the Supervisor.  In  TYMNET II, the Node Code
               allocates its resources dynamically.   The Supervisor sim-
               ply indicates  the nodes  through which  the circuit  must
               pass.




                                              Network Software    Page 24



          Network Specifications                            July 11, 1980



          C)   Tearing Down and Building Packets

               When a packet is received with a good checksum, it is torn
               down by  the Node Code, and  the data for each  circuit is
               placed into the  buffer dedicated to that  circuit.  Like-
               wise, when  a packet is  being assembled  for transmission
               over a link, data  is removed from the  buffers which con-
               tain data to be transmitted across the link.

               A round  robin algorithm is  used to build  records.  That
               is, once  a logical  record is made  for a  given channel,
               that channel  will not be  serviced again until  all other
               channels with data present have been serviced.

          D)   Flow Control

               Flow control in  a TYMNET network  is performed on  a per-
               channel basis.  Periodically, each node examines the buff-
               ers  associated with  each  input  process.  If  a  buffer
               exceeds  a threshold,  the  process  is informed  to  stop
               inputting for that port until further notice.

               For the link control process, a passive flow control tech-
               nique is used.  Periodically, each node informs its neigh-
               bors on  which channel it  is permitted to  transmit data.
               Each  time permission  is given,  a fixed  amount of  data
               (based on the throughput class of this circuit) is allowed
               to be transmitted.


          3.2.2 Supervisor Nodes                ________________


          Supervisor nodes in a TYMNET network  perform a variety of con-
          trol and data collection functions.  A Supervisor node contains
          the Supervisor and PROBE programs, a  number of disk files, and
          several "slave" programs  which are used to  transfer data from
          the data  files over  network circuits  to the  Network Control
          Center.  This  section discusses  all the  program modules  and
          data files  on the  Supervisor node.  It  should be  noted that
          Supervisor nodes have disk storage capabilities because some of
          the files maintained are very large.


          A)   Supervisor Backup

               Since a  TYMNET network is centrally  directed, provisions
               must be  made for  backup if  the network  Supervisor goes
               down.   (It should  be  noted that  in  a TYMNET  network,
               existing paths are not affected in the event of a Supervi-
               sor going  down.)  The solution  to the  Supervisor backup
               problem is to provide a  hierarchy of several Supervisors.



                                              Network Software    Page 25



          Network Specifications                            July 11, 1980



               Up to seven  supervisor nodes may  exist in a  TYMNET net-
               work.

               Only one Supervisor is active at  a time, and it keeps the
               others dormant  by sending them messages  called "sleeping
               pills".  If  the active Supervisor  goes down, one  of the
               dormant Supervisors will  awaken without any  human inter-
               vention and take  control of the network.   Although sleep
               times are staggered, it  is possible to have  two Supervi-
               sors trying to take control of the network simultaneously.
               This  solution  is  handled gracefully  by  assigning  the
               Supervisors  numbers indicating  their  priority.  In  the
               case of a Supervisor fight, the one with the lowest prior-
               ity will put itself to sleep.

          B)   Network Takeover

               In order to  control nodes and carry  out the Supervisor's
               function of building virtual circuits, the Supervisor must
               know the capacity of all nodes, their link capacities, the
               network topology  and (for  TYMNET I  nodes) the  value of
               every permuter table entry.

               A Supervisor starting network takeover has no prior knowl-
               edge of the network topology.   The Supervisor first sends
               a takeover  command to  its own node,  and learns  of that
               node's capacity, the capacity of its links, every permuter
               table entry in that node and the neighbors of that node on
               each link.  The latter is the  basis on which the Supervi-
               sor discovers the topology of the network.  The Supervisor
               now sends  takeover commands to  each neighbor of  its own
               node.  As each of these nodes comes under complete control
               of the  Supervisor, each  of its  neighbors is  checked to
               discover previously unknown  nodes, and these are  in turn
               taken over.

               In this way the Supervisor learns the topology of the net-
               work, all  its capacities and  (from the  permuter tables)
               which resources are  in use.  The node  takeover times are
               approximately 4 seconds  for a TYMNET I node  and 1 second
               for a  TYMNET II node.   The time determining  factors are
               the number of nodes, the bandwidth  of links in the vicin-
               ity  of  the  Supervisor, the  number  of  permuter  table
               entries and the connectivity of  the network vis-a-vis the
               Supervisor's  own node.   From  a  control standpoint  the
               Supervisor views the network as  a tree.  The control tree
               comprises a subset of the links  in the network.  The bal-
               ance and depth of this tree is the measure of connectivity
               of the network in relation to the Supervisor's own node.

               If a  previously non-operational link  becomes operational
               it may reveal one or more nodes that were previously inac-



                                              Network Software    Page 26



          Network Specifications                            July 11, 1980



               cessible.  The  Supervisor would  then extend  the control
               tree by taking over these  newly discovered nodes.  On the
               other hand,  if a link  that is  part of the  control tree
               goes out,  the Supervisor  loses control  of the  nodes in
               that subtree.  The control tree  is then rebuilt to regain
               control of  all the lost  nodes that are  still accessible
               through the network topology.

          C)   Circuit Building

               The primary job of the Supervisor  is to build circuits in
               the network.   Either a TYMSAT port  or a TYMCOM  port can
               request the  Supervisor to build  a circuit.   The request
               contains   a  user   name,  a   destination  host   number
               (optional), the origination node and  port, and a password
               (optional).  The Supervisor verifies the  user name in the
               Master User Directory (MUD).  See the MUD record format in
               the  ISIS Validation  User's Guide.   The Supervisor  then                    _____________________________
               checks for the correct password, if any.  To check a pass-
               word at login,  it is ciphered and compared  to the cipher
               in the MUD.  If no host  number is specified, the Supervi-
               sor uses the "home" host from the MUD as the host.

               The Supervisor now knows the node  number of the originat-
               ing port and the node number  of the destination port.  It
               then computes the minimum  cost path for the  virtual cir-
               cuit.  Each link has a cost associated with it.  This cost
               is a  function of the link  bandwidth and the  presence of
               overload conditions as  shown in  the table  below.  Addi-
               tionally, the  TYMCOM (host interface program)  may report
               an arbitrary host cost factor which  can be used to effect
               load balancing across hosts.

                             LINK COSTS IN A TYMNET NETWORK

                  LINE          NORMAL       1-WAY         2-WAY
                  SPEED          COST      OVERLOADED     OVERLOADED

                  56000 bps       10           26            42
                   9600 bps       11           27            43
                   4800 bps       12           28            44
                   2400 bps       16           32            48

               The minimum cost path as computed  by the Supervisor is an
               optimization  of network  resources rather  than a  dollar
               cost.

               Once a  path has  been plotted,  the Supervisor  allocates
               buffer pairs  and network link  channels on each  node and
               link over which the virtual  circuit will pass.  In TYMNET
               I, messages are sent to each node along the path to inform
               the node code  to allocate the appropriate  resources.  In



                                              Network Software    Page 27



          Network Specifications                            July 11, 1980



               TYMNET II, a "needle" is sent  to the node of origination.
               The needle contains the node number of the nodes which the
               virtual circuit is  to pass through.  This  needle threads
               its way through the TYMNET II nodes.  As it passes through
               a  node, the  node code  allocates  the needed  resources.
               Once the circuit  is built, the Supervisor  sends the user
               name, originating node and port numbers, a session number,
               and the terminal characteristics  to the destination node.
               It also sends a message to  the destination host to inform
               it that there is a new login.

          D)   Closed User Groups

               Any user  can be restricted as  to where he may  enter the
               network and what facilities he may  reach.  An access pro-
               file is used by the Supervisor  to determine which hosts a
               user may access.  The access profile  consists of a set of
               definitions  each specifying  a class  of permitted  entry
               points and set of valid destinations.

               A class describes a set of  node numbers.  A user may have
               more than one class assigned.  A  group describes a set of
               hosts.   Each class  may have  one or  more groups  and/or
               hosts associated with it.  (A class must have at least one
               group or host.)

               At login time, the Supervisor checks  the node the user is
               logging in through  against the classes in  the user's MUD
               entry and  determines the legal destinations  according to
               the groups and hosts assigned to those classes.  Access to
               a host  or from a  node may be barred  to the user  if the
               right information  is not found.   In this way,  access to
               hosts from various locations by users  may be tightly con-
               trolled.

               Default (or  home) groups and/or  hosts must  be specified
               (at least one per definition).  If a user does not request
               a specific  host at  login time, the  user will  be logged
               into the default  host, according to the  definition.  For
               even greater control, there is also a flag in the MUD that
               forces a user to  the home group or  host.  Access defini-
               tion can  also be used  to create prioritized  routing and
               multi-target routing.

          E)   PROBE

               A special program called PROBE runs  on the network Super-
               visor node.  PROBE  can be logged  into directly  and pro-
               vides the user  a means of monitoring  and controlling the
               network.  The PROBE commands are  discussed in more detail
               in the PROBE  User's Guide.  In general,  PROBE allows the                      ___________________
               user to check the status of the network or a network node.



                                              Network Software    Page 28



          Network Specifications                            July 11, 1980



               For example, PROBE can be used to find the number of orig-
               inations, terminations,  and pass-throughs  for any  node.
               PROBE can also be used to shut  a link or host so that new
               circuits will not  be built over the link or  to the host.
               Finally, PROBE can  be used to inspect the  error log file
               on the network  Supervisor.  Using the log  command, PROBE
               can be used  to monitor significant events  on the network
               in real time.

          G)   Error Log

               The  Supervisor maintains  a circular  file  on disk  into
               which it stores special messages received from the various
               network  nodes  or  hosts.  These  messages  include  such
               things as  duplicate hosts in  the network,  node takeover
               errors, host down, link down,  permuter table errors, link
               retransmission  errors,  MUD  error  found,  and  operator
               retake requests.   The error log  data may be  examined in
               real time by PROBE.

          H)   Accounting Information

               The TYMCOM  program controlling  the termination  port for
               any  circuit periodically  sends the  Supervisor a  record
               containing  accounting information.   In particular,  when
               the circuit is built, the originating  node and port, ter-
               minating node  and port,  user name,  session number,  and
               terminal type  are sent to the  Supervisor.  Approximately
               every 15 minutes another record is sent which contains the
               session number and the numbers of input and output charac-
               ter sent over the circuit since the last update.  Finally,
               when the  session is terminated,  a record  containing the
               reason for  termination is sent  to the Supervisor.   If a
               session is not terminated normally because of a failure of
               the node at  which the circuit terminates,  the session is
               treated (after an 8 hour wait)  as if it had terminated at
               the time the last update record was received.

               Accounting data  is received  by the  Supervisor in  frag-
               ments, not as complete records.   Each fragment is identi-
               fied  by a  session number.   The Supervisor  puts a  time
               stamp on  each fragment  as it  is received,  but does  no
               sorting of data fragments.

               The accounting data is sorted by the Raw Accounting Merger
               program (RAM).  RAM builds a  circuit to the slave program
               ACCOUNT,  which resides  on the  network Supervisor  node.
               ACCOUNT accesses and  reads the accounting data  file, and
               sends the data to RAM.  RAM sorts the accounting fragments
               into complete  session records,  and writes  the completed
               records to  tape.  Refer to the  RAM User's Guide  for the                                                ________________
               format of accounting records.



                                              Network Software    Page 29



          Network Specifications                            July 11, 1980



               As with the error log file, the  accounting file is a cir-
               cular file and thus the data  must be read before the file
               wraps around  and data  is lost.   This does  not normally
               pose a problem because the file is  very large, and a TYM-
               NET network can currently store up  to seven days worth of
               data before any is lost.  Also, to prevent loss of inform-
               ation, messages are stored in  the error log file whenever
               the  accounting file  exceeds 50  percent  of its  storage
               capacity.


          3.2.3 TYMSATs                _______


          Terminal control processes in a  TYMNET network are referred to
          as TYMSATs.  One of these processes  in the the customer's net-
          work is  the asynchronous  terminal controller  or Asynchronous
          TYMSAT.  There is both  a stand-alone version of  the Asynchro-
          nous TYMSAT and version which runs under ISIS.

          The Asynchronous  TYMSAT runs in  conjunction with  the 32-port
          Asynchronous board and is used  to handle asynchronous terminal
          ports which can run at speeds of 110 to 1200 baud.  The Asynch-
          ronous  TYMSAT can  control both  ASCII  type teleprinters  and
          2741-type terminals.

          A)   Terminal Identifier

               When the Asynchronous TYMSAT detects  the physical connec-
               tion of the terminal  (DSR and CAR high) it  prints a mes-
               sage asking the user to type a terminal identifier charac-
               ter (TID).  This message is printed  at either 300 or 1200
               baud depending on  the system  generation.  The  TID indi-
               cates the terminal speed and carriage return delay charac-
               teristics of the terminal.

          B)   Terminal Logon

               Once the terminal  type is determined, the  TYMSAT prompts
               the user for the login character stream.  This it sends to
               the network Supervisor for verification.

          C)   Control Characters

               A TYMNET network initially assumes that terminals are full
               duplex, odd parity, and cannot  respond to X-ON/X-OFF flow
               control characters.  To change  these characteristics, the
               user  may type  certain control  characters  in the  logon
               stream.   These characters  and  the  Auto-TID option  are
               explained in more detail in the TYMSAT Reference Manual.                                               _______________________





                                              Network Software    Page 30



          Network Specifications                            July 11, 1980



          D)   Echo Control in the TYMSAT

               The Asynchronous TYMSAT echoes most characters back to the
               terminal  unless the  terminal has  indicated  it is  half
               duplex by entering the appropriate  control character dur-
               ing logon.

               For full duplex terminals,  the Asynchronous TYMSAT echoes
               most characters  to the terminal.  For  certain characters
               such as the tab character,  however, the Asynchronous TYM-
               SAT defers the echoing to the host.

          E)   Automated Logon Facility

               The Asynchronous TYMSAT  design provides for a  user to be
               automatically connected to his destination  with no inter-
               action or  address selection on  his part.   This provides
               service for the specialized user who has no need to access
               multiple hosts.  This facility is described in more detail
               in the TYMSAT Reference Manual.                      _______________________


          3.2.4 Host Interfaces                _______________


          Host  interface programs  which run  in  network nodes  include
          Asynchronous TYMCOMs, X.25, X.75, 3270, and 2780/3780/ The typ-
          ical network contains  two types of host  interfaces; Asynchro-
          nous TYMCOM and  X.25 Each of the host  interfaces is discussed
          in general  terms here  and explained  in more  detail in  host
          interface supporting documentation.

          A)   Asynchronous TYMCOM

               The Asynchronous TYMCOM is  the simplest interface between
               a host  system and  a TYMNET network.   It appears  to the
               host system  as a bank  of low speed  asynchronous modems.
               This program runs under ISIS on the TYMNET Engine and uses
               the Asynchronous Board as its  I/O interface card.  It can
               emulate ASCII  teleprinter or EBCD or  correspondence code
               2741 devices.   The Asynchronous TYMCOM can  handle speeds
               of up to 1200 baud.  Refer  to the TYMCOM Reference Manual                                                  _______________________
               for more detail on the TYMCOM.

          B)   X.25 Host Interface

               The network connects to a customer  host's front end proc-
               essor over  a synchronous  link using  the X.25  protocol.
               This protocol is  handled by a program running  in an ISIS
               job slot and using the Synchronous  Card as its I/O inter-
               face.  The  X.25 program  conforms to  the CCITT  standard
               X.25 specifications.  Over  this link, it is  possible for



                                              Network Software    Page 31



          Network Specifications                            July 11, 1980



               programs running on the customer's  host to build circuits
               to hosts  on the network.  This  is done, for  example, by
               the accounting collection program  on the customer's host.
               It is also possible for terminals  on the network to build
               circuits through the network and over the X.25 link to the
               customer hosts.   The SIO card is  used as the  I/O device
               for HDLC framing.  Bisync framing  can be done through the
               SIO  card   or  the  synchronous   card.   Refer   to  the
               X.25_Interface_Reference_Manual  for more  information  on               ____ _________ _________ ______
               the X.25 interface.

          C)   3270 Host and Terminal Interface

               The 3270 Interface  is a host and  terminal interface that
               provides a 3270 connection for  TYMNET network users.  The
               interface provides services in  three basic modes:  native
               mode,  virtual  terminal  mode,  and  virtual  host  mode.
               Native mode provides a 3270 terminal user with access to a
               3270  support host  through the  network, eliminating  the
               need for dedicated leased long  distance lines.  In native
               mode, the 3270  terminal user  also has  multi-host/multi-
               application access on 3270 support computers.  This elimi-
               nates the need for duplicate  lines or equipment to access
               separate applications on the same or separate 3270 support
               computers.  Virtual terminal mode provides a 3270 terminal
               user  access to  any computer  on a  TYMNET network,  even
               ASCII support hosts.   The virtual host mode  provides the
               users of  certain ASCII CRTs  access to  computers running
               3270 applications.   This provides economical  dial access
               to both 3270  hosts and ASCII time sharing  systems from a
               single terminal.   The 3270  host and  terminal interfaces
               each   run    in   an   ISIS    slot.    Refer    to   the
               3270_Reference_Manual and  the 3270 User's Guide  for more               ____ _________ ______          _________________
               detail on the 3270 interface.

          D)   2780/3780 Interface

               The 2780/3780 interface  is a host and  terminal interface
               which provides  the 2780, 3780,  and 3770  series terminal
               user with access to host computers with 2780/3780 terminal
               support.  This service functions only in native mode, pro-
               viding an  economical connection between  remote terminals
               and hosts through  a TYMNET network.  This  eliminates the
               need  for  dedicated  leased  long  distance  lines.   The
               2780/378o host and terminal interfaces each run in an ISIS
               slot.  Refer  to the  2780/3780_Reference_Manual for  more                                     _________ _________ ______
               information on the 2780/3780 interface.








